
  Current: Configuration-Only Bases (Thin)

  # /core/models/request_base.py
  class CreateRequestBase(RequestBase):
      """Base for create requests - just config, no fields/validators"""
      pass

  class UpdateRequestBase(RequestBase):
      """Base for update requests - just config, no fields/validators"""
      pass


  The current pattern (thin bases + validation_rules.py) gives flexibility - domains can name fields differently (due_date vs target_date vs event_date).

   Current Pattern: Validated ✅

  Philosophy: Thin bases for config + reusable validators for behavior

  # Base provides config consistency
  class TaskCreateRequest(CreateRequestBase):
      title: str = Field(min_length=1, max_length=200)
      due_date: date | None = None  # Domain-specific name

      # Validators composed via assignment
      _validate_title = validate_required_string("title")
      _validate_due_date = validate_future_date("due_date")

  class GoalCreateRequest(CreateRequestBase):
      title: str = Field(min_length=1, max_length=200)
      target_date: date | None = None  # Different name, same validation

      _validate_title = validate_required_string("title")
      _validate_target_date = validate_future_date("target_date")

  Why this works:

  | Concern              | Solution                                            |
  |----------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
  | Config consistency   | CreateRequestBase, UpdateRequestBase                |
  | Validator DRY        | validation_rules.py functions                       |
  | Field naming freedom | Each domain declares its own fields                 |
  | Semantic clarity     | due_date means something different than target_date |

  The 2-line overhead per field (Field() + _validate_x = ...) is acceptable given the semantic precision it preserves. A task's due_date (hard deadline) is conceptually different from a goal's target_date (aspirational endpoint),
  even though both use validate_future_date().

